@node About "About TimePrefs"

	@{u}About TimePrefs. @{uu}

This is a simple little program that I wrote one day when I was extremely bored. 

I and many others dislike the Topaz-8 look when it comes to the standard preferences programs. The original programs that the old C= made aren't even font sensitive which makes them rather ugly on a 21" monitor 8). Yet there are some people see nothing wrong with Topaz-8 and think we're all crazy. I would guess that these people are probably still using Workbench 1.3 in a non-interlaced environment 8). (BTW. I know Topaz-8 got a face-lift - post 1.3) Well we could go on forever...

The program performs much the same way as the original Time preference program but it uses a few features of my 'everyday.library' and has some further options.

The main advantage of this program is that it uses @{"MUI" link MUI_Register}.

Mathew Wilson

	Contact me at:
	Box 6022, Halifax Street Post Office
	Adelaide SA, 5000
	AUSTRALIA

At present I can be e-mailed via David Cottrell

	dcottrel@adam.com.au
@endnode

@node Features "Time Prefs Features"

	@{u}Features.@{uu}

The program's interface is much the same as the original C= program with a few modifications. Its all pretty straight forward and won't bore you with an explanation of what you already know. However I'll just mention a few things.

The string gadget labeled 'Date:' enables you to manually type in the date using any of the vaild forms explained in the documentation of my progam 'On-Time'.

The calendar is Locale sensitive of course. The string gadget is not Locale sensitive in terms of the ordering of items. It senses language but not date ordering. It expects the format dd/mm/[yy]yy. This is because I use my own routine for date interpreting and not the system built in one. This may be changed a little later on but hey this is only a program that you'll use maybe once a year 8).

Unlike the C= Time preferences program, this version has the 'Edit' menu that contains the 'Last Saved' and 'Restore' options. These are usually used in reference to actual preference files stored in ENV: and ENVARC: Since the time is is not stored in a file 8) I think C= saw no need for these options. Well, I included them anyway as they instead make reference to the Battery Clock.

'Last Saved' will re-read the settings in the Battery Clock, displaying them in the interface.

'Restore'  will re-read the 'operational counter timer' of the computer and display the settiings in the interface.

When you select either 'Save' or 'Use', TimePrefs will send ARexx messages to Alarmist and OnTime to update.

Well, thats all there is to it.
@endnode

